{"title_page": "The Labour Party dossier into the handling of antisemitism", "text_new": "The Labour Party dossier into antisemitism (officially entitled '''<nowiki/>'The work of the Labour Party's Governance and Legal Unit in relation to antisemitism, 2014-2019'''') is a leaked [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] document written by party staff in response to the [[Equality and Human Rights Commission]]'s investigation into the party's handling of antisemitism complaints and includes reports of other forms of racism. The report reveals emails of senior party management staff, aligned with the right of the party, wherein there was clear obstruction of justice in dealing with cases of antisemitism and other noted cases of racism, and it does not clear the party of accusations of being 'institutionally antisemitic'. The report's main assertion is that rampant factionalism within the party had ultimately led to antisemitism and racism allegations not being dealt with properly.\n\nThe dossier was first reported by Tom Rayner, political correspondent at [[Sky News]], on Twitter where he reported that the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] lawyers had advised against submitting the report to the Commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/RaynerSkyNews/status/1249053545837604864?s=20|title=Exclusive: Labour lawyers decide an 860-page dossier on failures to handle AS complaints, compiled in last months of Corbyn's leadership, should not be sent to the EHRC. \n\nSome close to Mr. Corbyn are furious, with one saying: \"the truth must come out\"https://news.sky.com/story/labour-antisemitism-investigation-will-not-be-sent-to-equality-commission-11972071\u00a0\u2026|last=Rayner|first=Tom|date=2020-04-11|website=@RaynerSkyNews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/labour-antisemitism-investigation-will-not-be-sent-to-equality-commission-11972071|title=Labour antisemitism investigation will not be sent to equality commission|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The news of this dossier had many activists calling for its full publication; it finally leaked and spread through social media on 12 April 2020. On 13 April 2020, Labour leader [[Keir Starmer]] and deputy leader [[Angela Rayner]] announced an investigation into the report.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/siennamarla/status/1249722676295467012|title=NEW: Keir Starmer and Angela Rayner are commissioning an urgent investigation into the internal report.|last=Rodgers|first=Sienna|date=2020-04-13|website=@siennamarla|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> \n\n== Background ==\nThe Labour Party has been dealing with a rise in antisemitism complaints since the election of [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-45030552|title=A guide to Labour anti-Semitism claims|date=2019-07-16|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-GB}}</ref> While complaints proceedings over antisemitism and other forms of racism and discrimination had existed prior to Corbyn's election as leader, over the course of his leadership they seemed to have increased and worsened.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/1043524/labour-antisemitism-jeremy-corbyn-uk-antisemitism|title=Labour condemned for rise of antisemitism in UK - \u2018Friends and neighbours are afraid\u2019|last=Editor|first=David Maddox, Political|date=2018-11-10|website=Express.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> This has led to several serious issues in the party's approach to antisemitism and failure to deal with it, much of which is documented [[Antisemitism in the UK Labour Party|here]]. Much of the failings on dealing with antisemitism were associated with Corbyn's inaction<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/jeremy-corbyn-should-no-longer-get-benefit-of-the-doubt-over-rise-of-labour-antisemitism-1.473871|website=www.thejc.com|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>, however, this report lays bare the failings of former members of the senior leadership team, who opposed Corbyn's leadership, at the party's Head Office to take antisemitic complaints seriously.\n\n== Report's contents ==\nThere are several figures from the senior management team implicated in obstructing justice in antisemitism complaints, using defamatory language against MPs, staff and members, and hindering Labour's chances of winning during elections. The key finding shows that the named figures had not taken disciplinary cases seriously and intended for it to reflect badly on the leader. There is a report of a senior governance executive \"fabricat[ing] a case\" against people \"she doesn't like\", and one staffer admitted that \"real work\" was \"piling up\" while they \"were engaged in inappropriate factional work\". In the period between November 2016 and February 2018 the figures named in the report, who were in charge of member disciplinary procedures, had only taken action on 16% of all complaints made about members engaging in antisemitism.\n\nIn addition to this, there are clear examples of the named figures using insulting, derogatory and aggressive language towards Labour politicians, staff and members. This includes terms like \"trots\", \"bitch face cow\", \"fucking twats\". They repeatedly used derogatory mental health tropes, including terms like \"mentalist\" and \"nutter\", and repeatedly disparaged the appearance of party staff and members, using terms like \"pube head\", \"smelly cow\" and \"fat\". They also made comments saying that that certain party members should \"die in a fire\" and that a senior aide's \"face would make a good dartboard\". Labour MPs were also targets as they said that those MPs who nominated Corbyn should be \"taken out and shot\" amongst other disparaging remarks. Labour politicians who were insulted in the comments were: [[Ed Miliband]], [[Sadiq Khan]], [[Dawn Butler]], [[Diane Abbott]], [[Rachael Maskell]], [[Clive Lewis (politician)|Clive Lewis]], and [[Jeremy Corbyn]]. They also expressed anti-black racism and sympathy towards Islamophobic tropes. \n\nThere is also talk of violence against [[Jeremy Corbyn]]; talking about \"hanging and burning\" Corbyn, calling him a \"lying little toerag\", claiming \"death is too kind for LOTO ['Leader Of The Opposition']\". Senior management were found to be telling staff that they need not be \"comradely\" in their attitudes and statements about the leader.\n\nThere were constant talks of hoping Labour loses key elections in order to instigating a coup and remove Corbyn as leader. There were statements expressing that Labour should on the losing side for the [[2016 United Kingdom local elections|2016 local elections]] and [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 European Union referendum]]. Furthermore, there is overwhelming evidence of the senior management obstructing party efforts to win the [[2017 United Kingdom general election]] in order to remove Corbyn. The management team co-ordinated in \"refusing to share basic information to LOTO during the election\", created a \"parallel general election campaign\" and boasted about \"hardly working\" during the campaign. There are marked statements about their dismay at Labour over-performing expectations during the campaign, and apparent disappointment with the increase in seats after the election.\n\n== Reaction ==\nMany MPs, party members and activists within the Labour Party expressed dismay at the contents of the report. Many Labour politicians across the party's spectrum spoke out against the emails and practices revealed in the report<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AndyBurnhamGM/status/1249424188454076421?s=20|title=Yes, Ben, seems right to me. Always felt like the Party machine opposed my pro-public NHS & social care policies between 2010 & 2015. Not sure I had even-handed treatment from them in either the 2010 or 2015 leadership elections.https://twitter.com/_benbeach/status/1249419175895891980\u00a0\u2026|last=Burnham|first=Andy|date=2020-04-12|website=@AndyBurnhamGM|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/PaulaBarkerMP/status/1249662695466389504|title=Yesterday's leaked report laid bare the appalling antics of some at Labour HQ. We always knew they hated Jeremy, but I hope it is clear to those from other wings of our party that they deeply hated them too. (1/6)|last=MP|first=Paula Barker|date=2020-04-13|website=@PaulaBarkerMP|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/alexsobel/status/1249684628530761733?s=20|title=A thread on the leaked report on the Labour Party Governance and Legal Unity:\n\nI have campaigned for the Labour Party under 4 leaders and for candidates on every wing of the party putting my all into every campaign. \n\n1/5|last=home|first=Alex Sobel says stay|date=2020-04-13|website=@alexsobel|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/labourlewis/status/1249435425602707458?s=20|title=Anti Semitism has no place in our party. But it seems when black members and MPs call out racism in the Party, not only are they questioned and second guessed, they\u2019re it  insulted by own staff as well. Huh, who\u2019d have guessed it? @DawnButlerBrent had a point, as evidenced here.pic.twitter.com/xfbBYAmcZh|last=MP|first=Clive Lewis|date=2020-04-12|website=@labourlewis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>. Prominent Labour activists and supporters called for a full inquiry into the practices of the Labour Party<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/jon_trickett/status/1249436178379669504|title=Today\u2019s leaked revelations of alleged behaviour by the most senior Party staff following the election of  Jeremy Corbyn, when I was responsible for National Camapign Strategy are astonishing.\nThe report must be published in full.|last=Trickett|first=Jon|date=2020-04-12|website=@jon_trickett|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>. \n\nIn response to the report's leak, [[Keir Starmer]] and [[Angela Rayner]] issued a joint statement<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/siennamarla/status/1249723124901388290|title=Joint statement: \u201cWe have seen a copy of an apparently internal report about the work of the Labour Party\u2019s Governance and Legal Unit in relation to antisemitism. The content and the release of the report into the public domain raise a number of matters of serious concern.|last=Rodgers|first=Sienna|date=2020-04-13|website=@siennamarla|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>:<blockquote>\u201cWe have seen a copy of an apparently internal report about the work of the Labour Party\u2019s Governance and Legal Unit in relation to antisemitism. The content and the release of the report into the public domain raise a number of matters of serious concern. We will therefore commission an urgent independent investigation into this matter. This investigation will be instructed to look at three areas. \n\n# The background and circumstances in which the report was commissioned and the process involved.\n# The contents and wider culture and practices referred to in the report. \n# Third, the circumstances in which the report was put into the public domain.\n\nWe have also asked for immediate sight of any legal advice the Labour Party has already received about the report. \u201cn the meantime, we ask everyone concerned to refrain from drawing conclusions before the investigation is complete and we will be asking the GS to put measures in place to protect the welfare of party members and party staff who are concerned or affected by this report.\"</blockquote>\n\n== Criticism ==\nThere were concerns about the privacy and welfare of the complainants named within the report. An unredacted version was being circulated on social media, which led to worries of Jewish activists that they would be targeted by antisemites for speaking up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2020/04/why-keir-starmers-response-leaked-party-report-anti-semitism-right-one|title=Why Keir Starmer's response to a leaked party report into anti-Semitism is the right one|website=www.newstatesman.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nThe report was also criticised as being written to absolve the Corbyn leadership of the failure to deal with antisemitism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/antisemitism/status/1249285398783758342|title=Mammoth report by @UKLabour detailing anti- @jeremycorbyn conspiracy at Party\u2019s HQ is \u201clast ditch attempt to discredit #antisemitism allegations\u201d and must be sent to EHRC\n\nhttps://antisemitism.uk/labours-mammoth-report-detailing-anti-corbyn-conspiracy-at-partys-hq-is-last-ditch-attempt-to-discredit-antisemitism-allegations-and-must-be-sent-to-ehrc/\u00a0\u2026pic.twitter.com/ItkdeILPWx|last=Antisemitism|first=Campaign Against|date=2020-04-12|website=@antisemitism|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> However, the Executive Summary clearly states that it \"thoroughly disproves any suggestion that antisemitism is not a problem in the Party, or that. it is all a \"smear\" or a \"witch-hunt\". The reports findings prove the scale of the. problem, and could help end denialism amongst parts of the Party membership which has further hurt Jewish members and the Jewish community.\"\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Antisemitism]]\n[[Category:Labour Party]]\n", "text_old": "The Labour Party dossier into antisemitism (officially entitled '''<nowiki/>'The work of the Labour Party's Governance and Legal Unit in relation to antisemitism, 2014-2019'''') is a leaked [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] document written by party staff in response to the [[Equality and Human Rights Commission]]'s investigation into the party's handling of antisemitism complaints and includes reports of other forms